# Token Efficiency Rules

## Core Principles

- Be token efficient, but **never sacrifice correctness, maintainability, or clarity** for token savings.
- Prefer small, targeted changes over large rewrites.
- Always use Cursor's **"Apply"** feature for code changes instead of full regeneration when possible.

## Best Practices

- Make the smallest possible change that solves the problem correctly.
- Reuse existing code patterns instead of writing new code from scratch.
- Only load full architecture documents when absolutely necessary for the current task.
- When editing code, prefer editing small sections over rewriting entire files.
- Use focused prompts — be specific about what you need.

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- Do not regenerate large portions of code when a small diff would work.
- Do not load full architecture documents into context "just in case".
- Do not over-explain or add unnecessary comments for token savings.
- Do not sacrifice code quality to save a few tokens — it usually costs more tokens later.